Bid Alert No.:  22029809
Agency Bid No.:  Not Stated
Title:  D325--(WLR) VISN Contract for Package Tracking and Equipment.
Received Date:  02/24/2020
Close Date:  Not Stated
Delivery Point:  GREAT LAKES ACQUISITION CENTER 115 S 84TH ST MILWAUKEE WI 53214
Download documents online
Bid Documents
Specifications:
Under Statutory Authority 41 U.S.C. 1901 the VA Great Lakes Acquisition Center (GLAC) intends to negotiate a sole source contract with Pitney Bowes Inc. for Enterprise Mail Management Support for VISN 12. This acquisition is conducted under the authority of 41 U.S.C. 1901 Simplified acquisition procedures as implemented in FAR 13.501, only one responsible source and no other supplies or services will satisfy agency requirements. This will be a firm fixed price contract for base year plus four (4) one year (1) option periods. The NAICS Code is 532420. This Notice of Intent is not a request for competitive quotes. No solicitation documents are available and telephone requests will not be honored. However, if a firm believes it can meet the requirements it must furnish information about its products and services, as well as references from other customers who are using these products and service to the Contracting Officer by 8:00 AM (CST) February 25, 2020. Supporting evidence must be furnished in sufficient detail to demonstrate the ability to comply with the above requirements. Responses received will be evaluated however; a determination by the Government not to compete the proposed procurement based upon responses to this notice is solely within the discretion of the Government. If no responses are received, the Contracting Officer will proceed with the sole source negotiation with Pitney Bowes Inc. Capability statements shall be submitted by email only as a MS Word or Adobe PDF attachment to Frederick.Weddington@va.gov. TELEPHONIC INQUIRIES WILL NOT BE ACCEPTED.

Bid Alert No.:  220210231
Agency Bid No.:  36C25520Q0226
Title:  R702--WI - Patient Satisfaction Measurement Service
Received Date:  02/24/2020
Close Date:  02/27/2020  Est.
Delivery Point:  VA MEDICAL CENTER 4101 SOUTH 4TH STREET LEAVENWORTH KS 66048
Download documents online
Bid Documents
Request Future Documents
Specifications:
SOURCES SOUGHT NOTICE The Department of Veterans Affairs, Network Contracting Office (NCO) 15 is conducting market research to help determine the availability and technical capabilities of qualified vendors who can provide the Robert J. Dole VA Medical Center, Wichita, KS a comprehensive inpatient service satisfaction measurement service that both quantifies patient satisfaction and provide prioritized targeting for improvement. The service shall consist of development of inpatient satisfaction survey instruments that include customized questions and questions that permit comparison to other VA, non-VA facilities, and teaching facilities. The contract will be base with four option years. GENERAL REQUIREMENTS 1. Contractor shall possess minimum required Corporate Experience providing patient satisfaction surveys to federal government healthcare institutions to include VHA medical centers of similar size and complexity with high volume. Contractor shall submit Corporate Experiences with quote. 2. Contractor shall provide commercial and VA specific benchmarks with the capability to update every 3-6 months. Contractor shall submit with technical quote. 4. Contractor shall provide the Robert J. Dole VAMC (RJD VAMC) a means of transferring patient data that is acceptable to both parties. All patient information provided to the vendor shall be safeguarded under the terms of the Privacy Act and the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA). Contractor shall submit with technical quote. 5. Contractor shall provide onsite training two times per year Training Dates shall be coordinated with the designated facility POC. 6. Contractor shall provide virtual training as needed by the RJD VAMC. 7. Contractor shall establish a local Business Associate Agreement (BAA) with the RJD VAMC, unless a National BAA is already established prior to award. 8. Contractor shall meet quarterly with designated POC to review overall satisfaction to increase overall inpatient satisfaction by 2% or more. GENERAL REQUIREMENT FOR INPATIENT SATISFACTION The overall project purpose is to develop and acquire a health care consulting service that specializes in the creation, administration, and analysis of patient satisfaction surveys. The primary objective of this contract is to increase patient satisfaction at RJD VAMC in inpatient services by providing facility staff with real time feedback on patient perceptions that will enable employees to improve their performance and deliver excellent care. 1. The Contractor must use statistically valid data to benchmark using information gathered from other health care institutions that use similar survey instruments. The service must include a point in time (kiosk) survey tool that allows for immediate feedback (within 24 hours), accessible through an on-line Contractor portal. The database used must include information gathered from both commercial and VA hospitals, including the University Health Consortium teaching facilities and must allow for inclusion of customized questions for each location. This service must fulfill the American Nurses Credentialing Center (ANCC) guidelines for survey instruments that allow for hospitals that are following the Pathway to Excellence. Guidance given on the ANCC website states that hospitals should choose the highest quality tool that is statistically significant, at the broadest level nationally, with largest cohort to get the greatest comparative value . Contractors must ensure all survey benchmarking, reporting, and analysis will allow hospital to acquire/maintain Magnet Status. The results will be used to gain insight on the opinions of veterans who use our services. The information will include a detailed, comprehensive assessment of patient satisfaction at RJD VAMC. 2. The Contractor will be provided the following patient demographic information via encrypted file to utilize for survey and reporting purposes: Full name Last six of social security number Address Date of Birth Gender Military Service Era Email address Phone number All information must be safeguarded per all federal, state, and local guidelines. A Business Associates Agreement (BAA) must be signed by the successful offeror and all VA Information and Information System Security/ Privacy safeguarding guidelines must be followed. 3. The Contractor will provide assembly of data collected and professional analyses of the data is included in the services. The Contractor will provide quarterly reports of patient satisfaction in written form, also available through Contractor on-line web portal, within 10 days of the end of each quarter. The information will include quarterly comprehensive, detailed assessments of our patient s experiences while they are served at individual medical centers. The quarterly reports will also include a summary for all inpatient units surveyed. A sample of the quarterly report must be included in the Contractor s proposal. The on-line web Contractor portal must allow for the creation of customized Ad Hoc reports created by RJD VAMC staff using collected data. RJD VAMC inpatient units will be utilizing the service. They require full customization and specialty comparisons, including detailed findings and a full set of data queries available on-line and in hard copy. 4. The Contractor will provide the ability to query on-line data to evaluate satisfaction of services by patient care unit, site/specialty, survey receipt date, dates of services, clinician, and patient demographics in a timely manner. Please provide access to a Contractor on-line portal (web access) that demonstrates this ability in proposal. Government is not allowed to download a Contractor program to our information technology network. Specific deliverables are as follows: Development and provision of evidence-based survey instruments that enable measurement patient satisfaction. Survey questions must be approved by each participating facility prior to distribution. Distribution of survey by mail and by esurveys to patients within 72 hours of receipt of patient file from RJD VAMC POC and other POCs as specified in writing. Notify facility POC of all wrong addresses. Data entry for completed surveys Scanning of all surveys for daily viewing by selected RJD VAMC staff Contractor on-line web portal that allows for the creation of customized Ad Hoc reports created by RJD VAMC staff using collected data and Contractor created quarterly reports Access to program for on-line data analysis of RJD VAMC patient data by defined queries A survey tool that measures patient satisfaction with the following indices: Frontline staff courtesy and helpfulness Scheduling ease and accuracy Speed of registration process and length of wait Nursing staff (LPN, RN) courtesy and communication Provider courtesy and communication, quality of explanations, amount of face-to-face time with patient Office operations (hours of operations, cleanliness, etc.) Responsiveness of staff and sensitivity to the patient s needs Quality of the food The discharge process Pain Management Shared Decision Making Quietness of the hospital environment Overall rating of the hospital, outpatient clinic or emergency department Willingness to recommend Ability to add custom questions to the survey tools for each location On-line and/or in person education sessions/training for staff working with the program and accessing the data and reports. On-site annual data interpretation visits to each facility s Executive Leadership Team Unlimited customer service phone support during business hours. Subscription to newsletter/information on patient satisfaction, best practice, etc. Patient comments will be transcribed verbatim and available to RJD VAMC via the Contractor on-line portal SCHEDULE FOR CONTRACT TASKS AND DELIVERABLES The Contractor will be expected to contact each patient by RJD VAMC s preferred method of delivery. This contact may occur by mail, email, or point in time surveys to patients within three (3) business days of receipt of the patient information from RJD VAMC. The contractor will perform all necessary tasks to provide the quarterly reports within 10 days of the end of each quarter. Scanned surveys can be viewed by RJD VAMC staff electronically within 48 hours of receipt of the completed survey. Method of Evaluating Deliverables: RJD VAMC medical center staff will evaluate all deliverables and review the resulting data. These reviews will involve scrutiny of the data, viability of the information, and utility of the service in helping improve service to our Veterans, as well as the concurrence and/or changes required to proceed with the work as noted in the contractor s submissions. A Quality Assurance Surveillance Plan will be used to assure the success and failure of the vendor for meeting expectations. RJD VAMC staff will access the clinic account that checks the number of names/contacts sent from the inpatient services, compare to the number of surveys delivered, and analyze data from returned and processed surveys. Key Personnel and Temporary Emergency Substitutions 1. During the first ninety (90) days of performance, the Contractor shall make NO substitutions of key personnel unless the substitution is necessitated by illness, death, or termination of employment. 2. The Contractor shall notify the Contracting Officer, in writing, within 15 calendar days after the occurrence. 3. Specifications:
This contract provides the program management, engineering, logistics, requirements analysis, data management and analysis, public affairs and financial management support to both the EXBL and ExPO. Program management support consists of making technical and programmatic recommendations based on acquisition policies, such as Department of Defense (DoD) 5000 series regulations, and providing administrative, training, and limited information systems support. Title:  PeopleSoft RESTful APIs
Received Date:  02/24/2020

Bid Documents
Specifications:
Specifications include, but are not limited to: PeopleSoft FinanceThe original implementation of PeopleSoft Finance consisted of a separate PeopleSoft instance for eachparticipating campus. Between 2009 and 2012, these instances were combined into a single instance, managedcentrally and known as Consolidated Financial System (CFS). Campuses do not have direct access to the codebase or production system. They do, however, have third-party integrations that have been developed; whilethere are some common patterns, the catalog of integrated tools varies across the campuses. CFS also has acommon data warehouse for campus use; some campuses depend entirely on the central data warehouse whileothers have imported CFS data into their own data warehouses to provide greater reporting flexibility or tointegrate CFS data with other systems, including -- but not limited to -- the other PeopleSoft systems.PeopleSoft Human Capital Management (Human Resources)In the current environment, 23 instances cover all CSU campuses plus the Chancellors Office, with the COsharing an instance from a campus. While all instances start from a common code base and a standard set ofmodifications to address regulatory and policy needs of the system, individual campuses have the option ofsubmitting campus-specific modifications; for some campuses these modifications are extensive while for othersthey are minimal. However, the CSU has made substantial progress on a project called CHRS (ConsolidatedHR System) with a target completion date of 2023. When CHRS has been fully implemented, a single instanceof PeopleSoft HCM will be provided to support HR across the system. Most if not all integration work with HCMwill be timed to go live with CHRS as it comes in to production in 2022.PeopleSoft Campus Solutions (Student Information System)The Campus Solutions environment is both the most strategic, and the most complex component in CSUsenterprise environment. CS has been fully implemented for 22 of the 23 campuses, with a final campus in theplanning stage for an implementation in 2020-21. Similarly to HCM, there is a common code base provided bycentral support, but each campus has made additional modifications; in some cases, these modifications aresubstantial and extensive. While there are common patterns and some sharing of code, its likely that no twoinstances of CS in the CSU are identical.At this time there is no formal plan to consolidate CS instances. However, some campuses are evaluating theopportunity to manage costs and redirect resources by sharing a common instance with a higher degree ofmanagement provided centrally. The availability of a highly-capable integration layer is a strategic enabler withthe potential to accelerate movement in this direction. On the other hand, the extensive modifications made bysome campuses make it unlikely that complete consolidation will be desirable or feasible in the lifetime of thePeopleSoft system. Integration strategy most likely will require developing a standard API and then providingsome campus-by-campus specialization to accommodate all instances.
 
Product Code(s): 20911, 20810

Bid Documents
Attachment 1
Amendment 1 (02/24/2020)
Specifications:
Specifications include, but are not limited to: The Division of Contracts and Procurement has received a request to purchase maintenance for the jail's offender management system from a sole source vendor. County currently owns and runs the Offender Management System (OMS) software and several servers it resides on at the SLCO Jail. OMS is a County-owned asset. OMS is used for managing many facet sof the jails prisoner population. OMS is the foundation of jail operations. Without this tool, the jail would not be able to function effectively. OMS is the only place the Jails current and historical data is stored and is accessible in a useable format. Over the years, County has implemented customizations, such as the custom-built interfaces with 20+ of the Jails community partners and their software systems. The OMS software was originally created by Digital Solutions Inc. / Digital Solutions Inmate Telephone Inc. (DSI / ITI). Many years ago, Global Tel*Link Corporation (GTL) bought out DSI. GTL now has proprietary rights to the OMS software. Because of their proprietary rights to the OMS software, GTL is the only company in the world that can maintain, update, and/or modify the OMS software. GTL services their software themselves and they do not use other parties to service their OMS software.

Request Future Documents
Specifications:
2 1 Description The Program Contracting Office Central (PCAC) plans on submitting a solicitation in the next 30 days for the Department of Veterans Affairs (VA), Office of Asset Enterprise Management (OAEM) for the purpose of selecting a contractor to provide for updating the Strategic Capital Investment Planning (SCIP) Long-Range Action Plan summaries using revised data; creating new and updating current SCIP training materials, including SCIP Automation Tool (SAT) guidance documents; providing support for reviewing and validating the SCIP Action Plans; completing summary reports of the Action Plan final submissions; providing support for the validation of Business Cases; providing Help Desk staff to assist SCIP Users in the preparation of Action Plan projects and Business Case applications; facilitating the prioritization of the SCIP Decision Criteria; providing SCIP program management support; updating the current cost-effectiveness analysis template; conducting selected Capital Program Management Requirements Program (CPRMP) reviews and final documents; providing oversight support for execution of SCIP approved construction projects from 2012 through 2020 SCIP processes; providing support for the preparation of, and during select SCIP meetings via note taking, and providing a summary report of the meeting findings. This will be a combined synopsis/solicitation Indefinite Delivery/Indefinite Quantity (IDIQ) contract for commercial items prepared in accordance with the format in Federal Acquisition Regulation (FAR) subpart 12.6, Streamlined Procedures for Evaluation and Solicitation for Commercial Items, as supplemented with additional information included in this notice. This solicitation will be a request for proposals (RFP). The associated North American Industrial Classification System (NAICS) code for this procurement is 541611, with a small business size standard of $15 million. This will be a 100% set-aside for Service Disabled Veteran Owned Small Business (SDVOSB). Background: The Department of Veterans Affairs (VA), Office of Asset Enterprise Management (OAEM), is held accountable for meeting a number of requirements pertaining to its capital asset management. Capital asset initiatives, which include the enhanced-use lease (EUL) program and the Strategic Capital Investment Planning (SCIP) process, are coordinated to ensure capital investments are based on sound business practices and principles and, most importantly, meet Veterans health care, benefits and burial needs. Performance Period: This IDIQ shall be in effect for five years. The work on each task order placed under this IDIQ is anticipated to begin within thirty calendar days of award of the task order. However, each individual task order shall state the specific performance period. Type of Contract: This is anticipated to be a single award IDIQ contract. Firm Fixed price task orders will be generated with a detailed PWS and issued by a Contracting Officer. The maximum (ceiling) amount is estimated at $7,000,000.00 over a five-year performance period. The contract has a onetime minimum of $2,500.00. The contractor must demonstrate it possesses both general and specialized capability, knowledge, and skills. Place of Performance: The primary place of performance will be at the contractor s facilities; however, some task orders may require work to be performed at a Government facility (in such case, the place of performance will be specific in the PWS of the task order). Any work at the Government site shall not take place outside of normal business hours, which are generally between 7:30 am and 4:30 pm, or on Federal holidays or weekends unless directed by the Contracting Officer (CO). IDIQ Title: Strategic Capital Investment Planning (SCIP) Indefinite Delivery/Indefinite Quantity (IDIQ). The initial Task Order for this IDIQ will be solicited for simultaneously with the IDIQ solicitation. The magnitude of this first Task Order will be between $500,000 and $1,000,000. No questions concerning this solicitation will be answered at this time, as there will be an opportunity to submit questions after the solicitation has been posted. If you would like to send an email expressing interest in this project, that will be greatly appreciated. Point of Contact Emails expressing interest in this project should be sent to the Contract Specialist, Steve Mock at steven.mock@va.gov.

Title:  Pollution Prevention & Mitigation BAA
Received Date:  02/07/2020
Close Date:  02/06/2022
Delivery Point:  RONALD REAGAN BUILDING 1300 PENNSYLVANIA AVE NW WASHINGTON DC 20523
Specifications:
This Broad Agency Announcement (BAA) seeks opportunities to co-create, co-design, co-invest, and collaborate in the research, development, piloting, and scaling of innovative interventions for effectively mitigating air, water, and soil pollution, including ocean plastic pollution, electronic and other forms of solid waste in low and middle-income countries (LMICs). The United States Agency for International Development (USAID) invites organizations, companies, academic and research institutions, and investors to propose innovative approaches for preventing and mitigating pollution in countries to promote healthier populations, cleaner environments, and inclusive, sustainable economic growth. USAID&rsquo;s Office of Energy and Infrastructure (E&amp;I) within the Bureau for Economic Growth, Education and Environment (E3/DDI), in cooperation with regional and Global Health Bureaus and selected Missions, developed this BAA for Pollution Prevention &amp; Mitigation to improve the Agency&rsquo;s ability to assist partner countries in solving complex pollution problems that threaten sustainable development. This BAA seeks to engage with a wide range of actors within the global pollution sector to provide innovative interventions and technologies that further the U.S. Government&rsquo;s commitment to improving human health and the environment. Specific opportunities to do so will be provided through Addenda issued under this BAA.
